INTRODUCTION

The most important thing that those who want to be interested in the stock market should do is to learn how to analyze. In order to perform this analysis, as much data as possible should be monitored and the reasons for various movements should be investigated. In this project, approximately 7 years of data was given and an attempt was made to obtain the least erroneous version of the data. First of all, the companies with the least vacancies were determined, and among these companies, six companies from 3 different sectors were selected: Akbank, Garanti, Ford Otosan, Tofaş, Türk Telekom and Turkcell.

While drawing the Boxplot for these companies examined between 2014 and 2016, functions in the seaborn library in Python were used. However, while examining the data in general terms, outlier determination was made using the 3-sigma method. For this reason, not all points seen as outliers in the boxplot may be present in the 3-sigma output. However, since the 3-sigma method is a very reliable method, no changes were made. In fact, in some examples, it is seen that the frequency of outliers in the boxplot is high. In order to examine the outputs obtained from the code, weeks covering the 3 days before and after were determined and the developments in these weeks were investigated. Generally, sudden decreases or increases are caused by political, economic or global events within a day or two. What events they are and their effects are stated in chronological order below the graphs.

Google Trends was examined to investigate the changes in company stock values ​​and their correspondence with Google searches. Comparisons were made by looking at searches such as "IST:GARAN", stock market searches and searches in general. The connection between trend charts and stock price charts is clearly seen in the rest of the report. In places with negative outliers, there was generally little interest and few searches were made. Positive outliers are the peaks of Trend charts.

AKBANK

Red: Akbank, Blue: IST:AKBNK

Akbank’s 2014-2015 stock box-plots can be seen above.It is seen that the months with the most outliers are December 2014, June 2015. When we review the monthly outliers of the data between these years, it can be seen that they are on the following dates. Events in the 1-week periods including these dates can be seen below.

  • 16 December 2014
  • 17 December 2014
  • 8 June 2015

13 December 2014 - 20 December 2014

On December 16, 2014, the Central Bank of the Republic of Turkey (CBRT) increased the policy rate by 100 basis points to 10.75%. Additionally, the inflation rate was announced as 8.9%. This rate is the highest inflation rate in the last 10 years. High inflation increases risk perception and lowers stock prices. This caused Akbank stocks to fall, like all other stocks. This continues on December 17th.

05 June 2015 - 11 June 2015

When looking at Akbank stocks dated June 8, 2015, it can be seen that the outliers started with a sudden decrease compared to June 5 and continued until mid-day. There may be two reasons for this decrease, the first being the malfunction in Akbank's internet banking system on June 6, 2015 and the Turkish General Elections on June 7, 2015.

When we review the monthly outliers of the data between these years, it can be seen that they are on the following dates. Events in the 1-week periods including these dates can be seen below.

  • 28 November 2014

25 November 2014 - 01 December 2014

On December 28, 2014, the Central Bank announced that it increased interest rates. At the same time, Garanti Bank announced its third quarter profit, which is an increase of 27.5%, which is quite high. These two reasons caused a sudden increase in the stock price. However, since it remains in that range for a certain period of time in December, this may be a mean shift.

13 December 2014 - 20 December 2014

On December 16, 2014, the Central Bank of the Republic of Turkey (CBRT) increased the policy rate by 100 basis points to 10.75%. Additionally, the inflation rate was announced as 8.9%. This rate is the highest inflation rate in the last 10 years. High inflation increases risk perception and lowers stock prices. This caused Garanti stocks to fall, like all other stocks.

31 January 2014 - 6 February 2014

Observing outliers at the beginning of the months is not a bad sign. Since Outliers are viewed according to the monthly average, it is possible to see values ​​​​different from this value at the beginning of the month and there is no need for very important reasons.

11 December 2015 - 17 December 2015

The main reason for the sudden decline of Garanti Bank between 11-17 December 2015 was the poor performance of the bank in the financial report published on 14 December 2015. In the bank's third quarter balance sheet, its net profit decreased by 45% compared to the same period of the previous year, falling to 1.1 billion lira. This decrease was attributed to the decrease in the bank's loan interest income and the increase in loan provisions.

24 March 2014 - 04 April 2014

Looking at the data, March 27-28 and April 1 seem to be outliers. On March 27, Ford Otosan announced that it would open a new factory in Russia, and on March 28, Ford Otosan introduced a new model, Ford Kuga, in Turkey. These two events show that Ford Otosan stocks remain above the month's average and are a harbinger of its rise. The one on April 1st seems to be an outlier because it is below the average of April and it is not that important an outlier.

05 June 2015 - 11 June 2015

When looking at Akbank stocks dated June 8, 2015, it can be seen that the outliers started with a sudden decrease compared to June 5 and continued until mid-day. Türkiye's general election on June 7, 2015 may have caused this.

27 November 2015 - 03 December 2015

On November 30, it appears to be an outlier compared to the November 2015 average. This is not a major outlier as it depends on the decline that will happen in December.

09 August 2014 - 15 August 2014

On 12.08.2014, the stock price decreased just at 06.30 am and 06.45 am. The day's beginnings are not that much important while observing huge data like this. so, this cannot be called as an outlier, at least there can be no big reason for this.

14 December 2014 - 20 December 2014

A corruption and bribery investigation started in Turkey on December 17. Since Tofaş is one of Turkey's largest automotive manufacturers, company's share prices are significantly affected by Turkey's economic and political developments. The December 17 corruption and bribery investigation increased political uncertainty in Turkey. This uncertainty increased investors' perception of risk in the markets and caused Tofaş shares to decline.

21 August 2015 - 27 August 2015

The exchange rate crisis in the Turkish economy in the summer of 2015 increased uncertainty in the markets. This crisis increased investors' perception of risk in the markets and caused a decline in stock prices.

30 December 2013 - 05 January 2014

On 02 January 2014, the fluctuation in global markets may have negatively affected Turkish stocks.

25 March 2014 - 31 March 2014

March 28, 2014 is the day before the Feast of Ramadan. Even though the system has determined it as an outlier, the values ​​are not very different and it is natural to experience it before the holiday.

27 May 2014 - 02 June 2014

Although there was no obvious reason on May 30, 2014, Turkcell's stock prices increased towards the end of the day. The general reason may be the recently announced last quarter report and its successful progress.

28 July 2014 - 03 August 2014

On July 31, 2014, Turkcell announced a new investment plan and this plan was received positively by investors. As part of this plan, the company announced that it plans to invest in 5G technology and offer new mobile and fixed internet services.
